In Windows, when you want to uninstall (remove) a program from your computer, all you have to do is open the Add/Remove Programs dialog box from the Control Panel, select the program from the list and click the Add/Remove button. The program uninstall rou
tine should start and remove all the files and settings of the program from your computer, and also remove the program from the Add/Remove Programs list.
\par 
\par Unfortunately, this does not happen all the time. Sometimes, even after running the uninstall routine,
 you may find that the program is still listed in the Add/Remove Programs list. When you delete programs manually, they still remain in the Add/Remove list. After a while, you may notice that your Add/Remove list is full of unwanted items and programs tha
t are no longer installed on your computer.
\par 
\par }{\b\f1 Add/Remove Plus!}{\f1  is a small but useful utility that has been designed to help you manage the list with programs that can be uninstalled by Windows. Instead of uninstalling a program using the standard Windows Add
/Remove Programs dialog box, uninstall it with Add/Remove Plus! After removing the program from your computer, Add/Remove Plus! will ensure that the program is also removed from the Add/Remove list.
\par 
\par Add/Remove Plus! allows you to manage the Add/Remove Pro
grams list by deleting orphan entries, modifying the entries (including the uninstall commands) or by adding new entries to the list (it even supports drag and drop - dropping a shortcut to an uninstall program will add the program to the list!)
\par 
\par A great f
eature of Add/Remove Plus! is the ability to show you which applications are missing their uninstall program. These are usually applications that have been removed from your computer, but have remained in the Add/Remove list, due to a misbehaved uninstall
er. They are only cluttering the list and should be removed, but not before checking that they are really gone. This can be accomplished by trying to run their uninstall program (the one that is probably missing).
